{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778126027,"nonce":"/fNu2jnK/XNVuRVHut3e94z63BQ=","message":"## Why git-lfs was rejected + the sentinels alternative (preserving the analytical context)\n\nThe project-structure proposal subagent considered both git-lfs and a sentinels-based single-tree alternative. Documenting the reasoning here since the tradeoff discussion only lived in the transient analysis doc (\\`tmp/project_structure_proposal.md\\` above the repo).\n\n### git-lfs — rejected\n\n- **Multiple concurrent worktrees** (~6 active at any time): git-lfs adds bandwidth/quota overhead per worktree.\n- **Figures churn fast** during iterative analysis: every iteration would push fresh blobs to LFS storage.\n- **Spec-by-default keeps binaries out of git** at root anyway: commit \\`spec.json\\`, conditionally commit small renders below threshold. LFS's main value (keeping the repo lean) is largely already achieved without it.\n- **Operational cost**: separate LFS quotas, hooks, fetch policies, recovery semantics; substantial workflow friction for marginal gain.\n\n### Sentinels alternative — single tree with \\`.heavy\\` markers\n\nSingle \\`experiments/\\` (not \\`results/\\` + \\`_artifacts/\\` mirror) tree, with each bulk-containing subdirectory carrying a \\`.heavy\\` sentinel file. Gitignore rules consult the sentinel.\n\n**Advantages:**\n- Simpler mental model — one tree, one place to look up a run.\n- One fewer top-level directory.\n- Co-locates spec + bulk for a given run.\n\n**Disadvantages (why we picked the mirror tree instead):**\n- Mixes 5 GB bulk with 4 KB spec at the same path — \\`du -sh experiments/\\` doesn't tell you committable-vs-heavy at a glance.\n- Breaks \\`cp -r\\` of a \"results-only\" portion — you'd have to filter out anything under a \\`.heavy\\` marker.\n- Complicates remote sync — \\`rsync\\` needs sentinel-aware exclude rules.\n- \"Committable surface\" becomes invisible — no easy way to ask \"how big is the part of this tree we actually track?\"\n- Less obvious to outside readers: \\`results/\\` + \\`_artifacts/\\` is self-documenting.\n\nThe mirror tree (chosen) keeps these one-liners trivial: \\`du -sh results/\\` is the committable surface; \\`du -sh _artifacts/\\` is the bulk; rsync of either is a single path.\n\nCross-ref: \\`/Users/mll/Main/10 Projects/10 PhD/tmp/project_structure_proposal.md\\` for the full proposal incl. figure-handling tradeoffs and the migration plan.","files":null}]}